
			ML1 -- Music Language 1

ML1 is a computer language. It tries to get at the potential for sound
production inherent in a small computer connected via MIDI to one or
more synthesizers.  Current sequencing software is oriented toward
Music, with an emphasis on generating and dealing with standard
music notation.  ML1 is designed so that it is easy to transcribe
standard music notation into ML1.  But ML1 can also generate sounds that
would be difficult or impossible to notate with standard music notation.

On the other hand, ML1 isn't ultimately flexible.  It does impose a
certain structure on the sounds it produces, and it is easier to notate
some things in ML1 than others.  Like standard notation it has its
strengths and weaknesses, but since ML1 is meshed in with current
technology it will become obsolete long before standard music notation
does. 

There are several elements to ML1:

	1) Notes
	2) Sequences
	3) Chords
	4) Parameters
	5) Dynamics
	6) Functions (not implemented in this version)

The first 5 (Notes, Sequences, Chords, Parameters, and Dynamics)
directly describe musical events.  A ML1 text that contains only those
elements is similar sheet music in what it describes.  The real strength
and uniqueness of ML1 lies in its functions.

				Notes
				-----

Here is an example of a note:

			c

By itself, this symbol represents middle c, and a ML1 program that
contained only "c" would generate MIDI signals to play that note with
a 1 second duration. 

Sharps and flats are represented by the "+" and "-" characters,
respectively.  Thus, "c+" plays a c sharp, just above middle c.  "e-" is
an e flat.  The "=" is a natural, so "b=" would play a b natural. 
Analogous to the key signature in sheet music, ML1 can be set to apply
default accidentals to a note.  For example, all "b" notes could be
treated as b flat.  This facility will be described when we get to
Parameters. 

The following ML1 program would play a c major scale, one note per
second, starting on middle c:

			c d e f g a b c/
			
The chromatic scale starting with middle c looks like this:

	c c+ d d+ e f f+ g g+ a a+ b c/ b- a a- g g- f e e- d d- c


The "/" character means "one octave higher", and will be explained in a
moment.  Notice that the notes must be separated by blanks on the line. 
The string "cdefgabc/" won't work -- ML1 needs the spaces. 

These 7 lower case letters ("c", "d", "e", "f", "g", "a", and "b") are
the "note name characters" -- ML1 treats them specially.  A note name
character, optionally followed by an accidental, defines a "note name". 
For example, "c+" is c sharp.  Out of context, we don't know which c
sharp -- it could be in any octave.
  
ML1 considers notes to occur in octave ranges that start with a c and
end with the b a seventh above.  Octave's are numbered from 0 to 9. 
Octave 4 is the octave that begins with middle c -- 4 is the default
octave number.  Any note can have an octave specifier attached. 
Octave's can be specified in 2 ways -- relative to the current octave
number, and by absolute octave number.  The "/" notation above is an
example of a relative octave designation.  Using absolute octaves, the c
major scale could be written

			c4 d4 e4 f4 g4 a4 b4 c5

Absolute octave numbers have an important property -- when one appears,
it sets the default octave number.  For example

			c6 d e f g a b c/

plays a c major scale 2 octaves above middle c.  Once the "6" appears,
all the notes following will be assumed to be in the sixth octave. 

The trailing "/", however, still means "one octave higher", or "c7". 
The "/" and "\" characters are "relative octave designators".  The "\"
means "one octave lower".  Relative octave designators only apply to the
note that immediately preceeds them -- they have no effect on the
default octave number.  Relative octaves can be "stacked" -- "c\\" is
the "c" 2 octaves below the current default octave number. 

A ML1 program consisting of the following two lines will play the same 10
note sequence twice:

		c\\\\ c\\\ c\\ c\ c  c/ c// c/// c//// c/////
		c0    c1   c2  c3 c4 c5 c6  c7   c8    c9

The important difference between the two lines is that the first line
leaves the default octave number at 4, and the second line leaves it at
9. 

Notes always exist in a context of a "current tempo".  In all the above
examples the current tempo has been the initial default tempo of 60
beats per minute.  ML1 can play music much faster than that, but it
always maintains an idea of a fundamental unit of time called a beat. 
The beat is very frequently subdivided into parts, in a way that will be
described when we get to sequences.  Notes can be any number of beats
long.  The following line illustrates this:

		7c 6d 5e 4f 3g 2a 1b c/

The first c lasts 7 beats, the d lasts 6 beats, the e lasts 5, and so
on.  The "1" in front of the b is redundant -- both the "1b" and the
"c/" last one beat.  There is no direct way to say, for example, that a
note lasts half of a beat.  Instead, the beat is subdivided by using a
sequence. 


				Sequences
				---------

ML1 uses the term "sequence" in a special way.  A sequence is a list of
notes that will be played one after another, enclosed in square
brackets, like this:

		[c d e f g a b c/]

This sequence plays a c major scale.  For long sequences it is sometimes
nice to have ML1 check to be sure that you really have the number of notes
in the sequence that you think do.  If a number immediately follows the
opening "[", and the number is followed by a blank, ML1 will treat the
number as a "sequence count".  Thus

		[8 c d e f g a c/]

will cause ML1 to detect an error, because there are really only 7 notes
in the sequence.  But
	
		[8c d e f g a c/] 

is a sequence with 14 sub-beats, or "counts".  The first c gets 8
counts, and the remaining notes get one count each.

A sequence can appear any place that a note can, and its total time is
the same as the time for an individual note that it might replace.  Here
is a short ML1 program:

		c d e f g a b c/
		* * * * * * * * 

Here is the same program with last note replaced by a sequence

		c d e f g a b [ c d e f g a b c/]
		* * * * * * * * ^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ^

Both of these programs take 8 beats  (8 seconds).  The eighth beat of
the last program is occupied by a fast 8 note scale passage.  If we
think of this as 4/4 time, each of the notes marked by a * would be a
quarter note, and the notes marked by a ^ would be 32nd notes.  

Remembering that a sequence can appear anywhere a note can, the example
could be expanded as follows:

		c d e f g a b  [c d e f g a b [ c d e f g a b c/]]
		* * * * * * *   ^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ^ ! ! ! ! ! ! ! !

This program also takes 8 seconds, but the last sequence happens in a
32nd note interval -- this is a short run of 256th notes.  At this point
we are in the vicinity of MIDI's fundamental limits, though with
practice the ear can pick up a little information from runs this fast. 

Since a sequence can appear anywhere a note can, the following is legal:

			c d 2[e f g]

If this is 4/4 time, it is merely a case of a quarter note triplet.  The
whole sequence takes two beats, and within those two beats there are
three notes.  A slightly more complex example is this:

			c d 2[2e f]

The sequence contains 3 counts, so we still have a triplet figure, but
with the "e" occupying 2 of the three counts.

Complex rhythms are easy to do with sequences.  Here is an example (pick 
a clear, precise voice for your synthesizer):

	c [2 d e] [3 f g [4 a e c e]] [5 b g 3g+] a b c/ c

Sometimes it is nice to be able to tie a note from one sequence to
another.  The underscore character, "_", is used to indicate this:

		c 3[7 4d e f g_] 2[7 _g a a a+ b 2c]  

There are a couple of interesting things to notice about that example. 
One is the tied g -- essentially what happens is that only the "note on" MIDI
signal is sent when a "_" character is seen following a note, and the 
corresponding "note off" isn't sent until an "_" preceeding the exact
same pitch is seen.  Another interesting feature is the complexity of
the rhythm -- this would be very difficult to notate with conventional
notation.  Notice that each of the sequences is 7 sub-beats long, but
that the total durations are different.  The duration of the "d" in the
first sequence is 12/7 ths of a second.  The duration of the g is 3/7 +
2/7 or 5/7 of a second.  Finally, notice the "3[7 4d".  It couldn't be
written without the space between the "7" and the "4".  What would 
"3[74d e f g_]" mean?  It could mean "3[74 e f g_]", a sequence of 74
sub-beats that was incorrectly written, or it could mean "3[ 74d e f
g_]", which would be a sequence of 77 sub-beats, with 74 of them applied
to the first note.  In fact, it would mean the latter.  ML1 only uses
the first number inside a "[" to mean a sequence count if it is
separated from the contents of the sequence by a space.


				Chords
				------

Sequences order events in time.  Frequently one wants to have events occur
at the same time.  In ML1, if things are enclosed in braces "{" and "}",
then they happen at the same time.  Furthermore, each item in the chord
takes the same amount of time.  For example,

			3{c e g}

is a c major chord that lasts 3 beats -- each note inside gets the full
three beats.

Chords can also appear anywhere a note can.  Chords can appear in
sequences and sequences can occur in chords.  From this you can see that
the term "chord" is really a little misleading.  What ML1 calls a chord
is really a general simultaneous grouping.  For example,

		[{c e} {d f} {e g}]

represents a triplet run of thirds.  This could also be notated as

		{ [c d e] [e f g] }

ML1 doesn't care about lines, so it might be better to write the
preceeding example as

		{ [e f g]
		  [c d e] }
or maybe even as

		{
		  [e f g]
		  [c d e]
		}

In transcribing contrapuntal music or orchestral music, where one thinks
of the music as parallel sequences, it works out fairly neatly to
organize it something like the following example:

12{
   [12 c5 c d | e e f | g g a | [f+ g f+] [g f+ e= f+] g_  ]
   [12 2c3  r | c c d | e e c | d         c            b=\ ]
}

This example is the beginning of a simple minuet by Bach.  It continues
like this:

12{
  [12 -o5 [_g a] [f= e=] f_ | [_f g] [e d] e | [c b=\] c d | 3g\             ]
  [12 -o2 2b             a= | 2a           g | 2a        f | g [g3 f] [e3 d] ]
}

Several new things are introduced by these examples.  First of all, the
letter "r" in the second sequence means "rest".  It is considered to be
a note name character, just like "c", but it doesn't make any noise. 

This piece is in 3/4 time, and each set of braces represents 4 measures. 
The "12" preceeding each opening brace ("{") means that the "chord" is
12 beats long.  However, each of the parallel sequences is also 12 long,
so the individual notes inside end up being 1 second (or one beat) each. 
The "|" marks are measure marks.  ML1 really doesn't pay any attention
to them, but experienc has taught that it really helps to have some mark
like that available to keep track of where you are.

Notice the "-o5" and the "-o3" strings in the third and fourth
sequences, respectively.  The "-o" means "set the default octave". 
These are "Parameters", and they will be explained in the next section.

Notice that some attempt has been made to keep notes that sound at the
same time in vertical alignment.  It isn't really necessary, but it
helps a great deal when transcribing music.  ML1 is a very terse
language, and it is extremely easy to loose your place while you are typing.

ML1 doesn't know anything about the vertical alignment, however.  It
always reads characters left to right, one line after another.  As far
as ML1 is concerned these examples might as well be written this way:

12{[12 c5 c d e e f g g a [f+ g f+] [g f+ e= f+] g_] [12 2c3 r c c d e e 
c d c b=\]} 12{[12 -o5 [_g a] [f= e=] f_ [_f g] [e d] e [c b=\] c d 3g\ 
] [12 -o2 2b a= 2a g 2a f g [g3 f] [e3 d]]}

You would go blind or insane in a short time if you tried to read stuff
like this.

				Parameters
				----------

We just saw an example of a parameter.  Here are some more -- the actual
first line of the Bach minuet looks like this:

		-t108 -ac e- -ac b- -ac a-

This line reads "set the default tempo to 108 beats per second, set the
default accidental for e to flat, the default accidental for b to flat,
and the default accidental for a to flat".  That is, set the key
signature to c minor.  These are all examples of parameters. 

A parameter always begins with a dash.  After the dash comes an
abbreviation for the parameter name.  After the parameter name may come
a number, or a note name, or anything else that is appropriate for the
particular parameter setting.  The current parameters are:

	-ac	-- set accidental (using a note name, default all naturals)
	-ch	-- set MIDI channel (0-15, default 0)
	-v	-- set overall volume (0-127, default 64)
	-o	-- set default octave number (0-9, default 4)

Other parameters are in the works.


				Dynamics
				--------

Two marks can be used to change the relative volume of a note, sequence
or chord.  The "emphasize" character is the "!", and it multiplies the
volume (as represented by the MIDI velocity number) by about 1.1.  The
"subdue" character is the "?", and it multiplies the MIDI velocity
number by about 0.9.  These operators can be stacked, like the relative
octave designators.  The following ML1 program plays a short scale
gradually increasing in volume:

		???c ??c ?c c !c !!c !!!c

Dynamic marks are like relative octave designators, in that they only
change the volume of the entity to which they are prefixed.  This might
seem to be a severe limitation, but in practice it isn't, since the
operator can be applied to whole lines of music making the line into a
sequence, and prefixing the sequence with the appropriate dynamic
marking. 


	Scope, Operator Order, and Other Technical Details
	--------------------------------------------------

Sequences, chords, and functions are nested constructs.  That is, they
define a strict hierarchy wherever they occur -- one can't overlap
another.  For example,

			{ [...] [...] {...} } 
			[ {...} { [...] [...] } ]

are correctly nested.  On the other hand, strings like "{ [ } ]" are
illegal.  The first line is a chord that strictly contains two sequences
and a subsidiary chord.  The second line is a sequence that contains two
chords.  The second chord itself contains two sequences.  Sometimes it
is clearer to indicate the levels by using extra lines and indentation. 
The above two lines might be more clearly represented as

		          ---->0
		{         ---->1
		  [...]   ---->2
		  [...]   ---->2
		  {...}   ---->2
		}         ---->1
		          ---->0
		[         ---->1
		  {...}   ---->2
		  {       ---->2
                    [...] ---->3
		    [...] ---->3
		  }       ---->2
		]         ---->1
		          ---->0

(Here a "nesting level" number has been added.)

The scope of an operator or value is the 


abstractions are rich enough to define interesting music.
be defined 
interesting philosophical question as to whether
are powerful enough to

As indicated above, ML1's basic understanding of a program is as a
linear string of charcters.  The scope of an operation or value is the
substring of characters over which it is valid or constant.  In all
cases ML1 follows two rules to determine scope.  The first rule has to
do with the notion of "levels of nesting".  Sequences, chords, and
functions are nested constructs. 


